&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Spinal Cord Stimulation and Rehabilitation in Children with Cerebral&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;FOR CLINICIANS AND RESEARCHERS. NOT SUITABLE FOR PATIENTS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Drs. Jason Carmel and Katherine Dimitropoulou would like to invite you to join the Weinberg Family Cerebral Palsy Center on&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Friday, March 17&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, 2023&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;for the third lecture of the 2023 Movement Recovery Seminar Series. &lt;em&gt;Siddhi Shrivastav, MS and Charlotte Caskey, MS &lt;/em&gt;of the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fdepts.washington.edu%2Fmoritlab%2F&amp;amp;data=05%7C01%7Cjmc2475%40cumc.columbia.edu%7C1dfc842771774ca40a9a08db20b7694a%7Cb0002a9b0017404d97dc3d3bab09be81%7C0%7C0%7C638139744355579052%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;amp;sdata=wvINvp%2FcegL7ThPGmqJas5cmOc3F5OOuKpcMpZsAh98%3D&amp;amp;reserved=0"&gt;Restorative Technologies Laboratory&lt;/a&gt; at the University of Washington &lt;/strong&gt;will be presenting the talk below from 12:00-1:00PM&amp;nbsp;via Zoom.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Background:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cerebral Palsy (CP) is caused by damage to the developing brain and results in spasticity and impaired movement. Transcutaneous spinal stimulation (tSCS) is a non-invasive method to modulate the physiological state of the spinal cord, with promising results in people with spinal cord injury.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Early results suggest that tSCS may also benefit children with CP by influencing afferent pathways.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Combining tSCS with gait training may improve function by modulating spinal excitability and reducing spasticity.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We evaluated the effects of tSCS combined with short burst interval locomotor training (SBLTT)3 on gait function and spasticity in two children with CP.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To register, please email cpresearch@cumc.columbia.edu&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Join Columbia&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;Department of&amp;nbsp;Public Safety in a situational awareness training.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What is Situational Awareness?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Situational Awareness&amp;nbsp;is a critical life skill, and entails being aware of where you are and to what is happening around you; being alert to potential threats to your health and safety and being cognizant of emergency exits and other paths to safety.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What Will The Training Focus On?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this training, you will learn:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How the Fight-or-Flight response affects your safety&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How&amp;nbsp;situational&amp;nbsp;awareness&amp;nbsp;can keep you safe&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;What are the odds?&amp;rdquo;-being informed to make good decisions for your personal safety&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Techniques to develop&amp;nbsp;awareness&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Personal safety resources&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Run. Hide. Fight. &amp;ndash; a strategy for your personal safety in emergency situations&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RSVP is required.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;After you complete your registration, you&amp;#39;ll receive a confirmation email containing the Zoom link&amp;nbsp;for joining the event.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

