&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Beyond Marco Polo: Venice and the Mongols in the 13th-15th Centuries&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Presenter:&lt;strong&gt; Nicola di Cosmo, &lt;/strong&gt;Institute for Advanced Study, Princeton&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Moderator: &lt;strong&gt;Pier Mattia Tommasino&lt;/strong&gt;, Italian Department, Columbia University&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The enormous influence of Marco Polo&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;Travels&lt;/em&gt; in Medieval and Renaissance literature, rekindled recently by the suggestion that he may not have been in China after all, has conditioned and often obscured the historical assessment of Venice&amp;rsquo;s engagement with Mongol rulers and its activities in the East. &amp;nbsp;This talk aims to reorient the discussion, showing motivations, obstacles, limitations and achievements of the Venetians who lived, traded and often died in Mongol lands. It will also discuss&amp;nbsp;the differences between Venice and Genoa in their engagement with Asian rulers and establishment of colonies on the Black Sea and in Iran.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This event is co-sponsored by the Italian and Mediterranean Colloquium, the European Institute, and the Weatherhead East Asian Institute.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This free webinar is suitable for anyone with an interest&amp;nbsp;in cerebral palsy. This webinar will be recorded.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jan 26, 2023,&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;19:00-20:00 US Eastern Time (New York Time Zone)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Weinberg Family Cerebral Palsy&amp;nbsp;Center (WFCPC) - Health and Wellness Webinar Series&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3 Myths About Cerebral Palsy&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join the WFCPC&amp;#39;s Executive Director and Research Director,&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.weinberg.cuimc.columbia.edu/profile/jason-b-carmel-md" target="_blank"&gt;Jason B. Carmel MD, PhD&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;as he uncovers 3 myths about cerebral palsy and explains them through&amp;nbsp;the latest science. We will discuss genetics and progression of cerebral palsy, and the treatment roadmap based on our &lt;a href="https://www.weinberg.cuimc.columbia.edu/research/movement-recovery-laboratory" target="_blank"&gt;center&amp;#39;s research&lt;/a&gt; and that done in the field.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Carmel is a child&amp;nbsp;neurologist and motor system neuroscientist. He is the Director of the WFCP&amp;#39;s &lt;a href="https://www.weinberg.cuimc.columbia.edu/research/movement-recovery-laboratory" target="_blank"&gt;Movement Recovery Laboratory&lt;/a&gt; which investigates the function and repair of the central nervous system.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;Weinberg Family Cerebral Palsy&amp;nbsp;Center is a part of Columbia University Irving Medical Center and NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital. Through comprehensive medical care, research and education programs, we aim to expand knowledge of cerebral palsy&amp;nbsp;and access to care across the life span.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.weinberg.cuimc.columbia.edu" target="_blank"&gt;www.weinberg.cuimc.columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

