&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Brazil Seminar:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Fintech, Development, and Financial Inclusion in the Global Economy&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Speaker(s):&lt;strong&gt; Frederic de Mariz&lt;/strong&gt;, Head of LATAM EGS, UBS; Lecturer in Sustainable Finance, SIPA&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Date and time: November 9th, 6:10 pm&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Brazil Seminar is a practicum designed to discuss contemporary Brazil&amp;#39;s major economic, political, and social problems with leading analysts, activists, business leaders, and public figures. The seminar is unusual in its reliance upon a stream of outside speakers rather than on a fixed syllabus and set of lectures by the instructor only. Former participants include cabinet members, senior representatives of international organizations, academics, civil society activists, and other world-class experts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During the Fall term, we will primarily focus on social and political factors while also addressing economic and financial issues. We also prioritize a practitioner&amp;rsquo;s perspective, using Brazil as a reference to discuss challenges that developing nations face in their development path.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This event will be live streamed on the &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7xFphhjpuprNnkUQiOykRQ"&gt;ILAS Youtube page.&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A lecture by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Kabage Karanja&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Stella Mutegi&lt;/strong&gt;, founders of&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.cave.co.ke/"&gt;Cave_bureau&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;and Adjunct Assistant Professors at Columbia GSAPP.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Response by Assistant Professor&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Lola Ben-Alon&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and Adjunct Assistant Professor&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Lindsey Wikstrom&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cave Bureau is a Nairobi-based architecture and research studio that charts explorations into architecture and urbanism within nature. Their work addresses the anthropological and geological context of the postcolonial African city as a means to confront the challenges of our contemporary rural and urban lives.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This lecture will be held in person and is accessible to Columbia University affiliates with a valid green pass, and will be live-streamed for the general public on the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/user/ColumbiaGSAPP/videos"&gt;GSAPP YouTube Channel&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This event content is equivalent to 1 AIA/CES total learning credit, 1 total credit earned. AIA. Please contact&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="mailto:events@arch.columbia.edu"&gt;events@arch.columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;for more information.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Webinar: &amp;ldquo;Visualizing Science: Persuasive Storytelling&amp;rdquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thursday, Nov. 10 from 9 a.m. to 11 a.m.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Piles of psychological research literature tell us what we already know: humans are terrible at decision-making. We don&amp;rsquo;t really use reasoning. We don&amp;rsquo;t really consult the data. Most of our decisions &lt;strong&gt;are based on emotions and gut instinct&lt;/strong&gt;. So how can you communicate data with policy-makers, business leaders, the public, and anyone else who needs to be persuaded to accept and possibly act on research? In this talk, we&amp;rsquo;ll cover some key insights from persuasion science and how we can leverage storytelling and data visualization to maximize our impact.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Presentations by:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bill Shander&lt;/strong&gt;, Founder of Beehive Media&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eleanor Lutz&lt;/strong&gt;, Graphics Editor at &lt;em&gt;The New York Times&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jen Christiansen&lt;/strong&gt;, Senior Graphics Editor at &lt;em&gt;Scientific American&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Followed by a Q&amp;amp;A session.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Open to Columbia faculty, graduate students, postdocs, and WeConnect communicators.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;After registering, you will receive a confirmation email containing a Zoom registration link in order to join the webinar&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;If you have questions or encounter problems registering, please contact Cassandra Nathan at &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="mailto:cm2891@columbia.edu"&gt;&lt;em&gt;cm2891@columbia.edu&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

