&lt;h2&gt;Four Ways to Manage Your Large Course (for Faculty)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute workshop for Columbia Faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;How do I engage and build community with students in my large course? How can I promote academic integrity when I have so many students? How can I work with my TAs effectively?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this session, you will have an opportunity to address these questions and reflect on strategies that are scalable for varying sizes of large courses. Join us in discussing ways to promote classroom community, active learning, and academic integrity to make large courses more manageable and rewarding for faculty and students alike.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/resources/teaching-large-courses/"&gt;Teaching Large Courses Effectively and Efficiently&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Engaging Students with Poll Everywhere (for Instructors)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 30-minute demo session for Columbia Faculty and Graduate student instructors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Are you seeking a way to gauge what your students are thinking and learning in the classroom in real-time? Want to immediately display and use the results from students through in-class polling?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Experience a short demonstration of &lt;a href="https://www.cuit.columbia.edu/live-polling"&gt;Poll Everywhere&lt;/a&gt;, an in-class polling and quizzing tool that allows you to pose various types of questions to better understand what students are learning and collect their feedback. This will be followed by opportunities to ask questions and to reflect on how you might intentionally integrate Poll Everywhere into your teaching context.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Unable to join us for this demo and Q&amp;amp;A? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/tech-resources/ars/"&gt;Poll Everywhere: Audience Response Systems&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Planning Your Lectures Based on the Science of Learning (for Faculty)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute session for Columbia faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;How can I plan my lectures to better help my students learn? How can I promote student engagement with course material in addition to listening to my lectures?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Come address these questions with us! We will discuss findings from the science of learning&amp;mdash;activating prior knowledge, practicing retrieval, and reflecting&amp;mdash;and simple ways you can incorporate them so students can further engage with course material. You will also have an opportunity to draft a plan for an upcoming class session and hear how your colleagues engage their learners during lectures.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resources: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/engaged-lecturing/"&gt;Five Tips for Engaged Lecturing&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/sapp/active-learning-learner-perspective/"&gt;Active Learning: The Learner&amp;#39;s Perspective&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This session will provide strategies and supports to ensure teaching is equitable, accessible, and inclusive for ALL students, including (but not limited to) multilingual learners, students with disabilities, and first-generation students. The session will begin by providing the objectives and principles of Universal Design for Learning (UDL), how UDL contributes to anti-racist and anti-ableist practices, and end with examples of equitable, accessible, and inclusive course delivery methods and assignments.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Columbia is an institutional member of the National Center for Faculty Development &amp;amp; Diversity (NCFDD).&lt;/p&gt;
