&lt;li&gt;Activate your free membership here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://tinyurl.com/columbiaNCFDD"&gt;https://tinyurl.com/columbiaNCFDD&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.facultydiversity.org/webinars/newfacultydiscussion" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;REGISTER&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;on the NCFDD website.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Teaching with CourseWorks (for Instructors)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 90-minute session for Columbia Faculty and Graduate student instructors.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join us in exploring how to create community, support student engagement, and assess student learning using CourseWorks, Columbia&amp;rsquo;s learning management system. This workshop will give you an overview of the CourseWorks interface and highlight a toolset that will allow you to set up a course with clear expectations for students, create opportunities for a variety of assignment engagements, and nurture an environment that encourages a culture of inclusive communication.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;By the end of the session, participants should be able to:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Determine which CourseWorks tools will meet the teaching and learning goals of their course(s).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intentionally integrate CourseWorks into their courses.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please note that this session takes place via Zoom. Before you attend this session, we recommend that you familiarize yourself with Zoom. You can access CUIT&amp;rsquo;s zoom training sessions on their &lt;a href="https://cuit.columbia.edu/zoom#/text-13566"&gt;Zoom training page&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Check the &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt; for future offerings of this workshop. Engage with our asynchronous offerings on this topic: &lt;a href="https://courseworks2.columbia.edu/enroll/M9LDJW"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Introduction to CourseWorks (Canvas) Online&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (self-paced course), &lt;a href="http://bit.ly/ctl-canvas-grading-enroll"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assessment and Grading in CourseWorks (Canvas)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;(self-paced course, and &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/courseworks/"&gt;Teaching with CourseWorks&lt;/a&gt; (on-demand resource); or receive customized assistance through &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/get-help/"&gt;office hours&lt;/a&gt;, or by scheduling a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Setting Up Assignments, Quizzes, and Discussions in CourseWorks (for Instructors)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 30-minute session for Columbia Faculty and Graduate student instructors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join us to learn best practices to create Assignments, Quizzes, and Discussions in CourseWorks, Columbia&amp;rsquo;s learning management system. Experience a walk through of these commonly used tools and see how CourseWorks displays graded work. You will also gain an understanding of available options and features such as giving assignments different weights, and adding extra time to quizzes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/courseworks/"&gt;Teaching with Courseworks&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Teaching in the Morningside eClassroom (for Instructors, Course and Teaching Assistants)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute session for Columbia Faculty, Graduate student instructors, course and teaching assistants.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Are you wondering about the technology available in&amp;nbsp;Morningside classrooms equipped by CUIT to support teaching and learning? Would you like to learn more about the hybrid technology in Morningside classrooms and the support available to you&amp;mdash;both pedagogical and technological&amp;mdash;to enhance the courses you teach?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Whether you are new to teaching in Morningside classrooms or seeking a refresher, this joint session offered by Columbia University Information Technology (CUIT) and Columbia Center for Teaching and Learning (CTL) is for you!&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn about and experience a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://cuit.columbia.edu/classroom-locations" target="_blank"&gt;hybrid classroom&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;environment on Morningside campus, equipped by CUIT to enhance face-to-face instruction as well as support in-person and remote students. We will provide an overview of classroom technology, share pedagogical resources, and leave lots of time for questions.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join us and imagine the possibilities in your classroom!&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Note:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;This session will be held in 402 Chandler on&amp;nbsp;Morningside campus. Registered participants can choose to participate in-person or via Zoom.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Unable to join us for this session?&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Learn more about Morningside hybrid classrooms and CUIT eclassroom support&amp;nbsp;-&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://cuit.columbia.edu/hybrid-class-checklist" target="_blank"&gt;Hybrid Classrooms: Getting Started Checklist&lt;/a&gt;; Registrar-managed&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://cuit.columbia.edu/classroom-locations" target="_blank"&gt;Hybrid Classroom Locations&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; Explore the CTL&amp;rsquo;s portfolio of resources, including&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/five-tips-hybrid/" target="_blank"&gt;Five Tips for Hybrid/HyFlex Teaching with All Learners in Mind&lt;/a&gt;;&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/hyflex/" target="_blank"&gt;Hybrid/HyFlex Teaching and Learning&lt;/a&gt;; and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/flexible-spaces/" target="_blank"&gt;Teaching in Flexible Learning Spaces&lt;/a&gt;; receive customized assistance through&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/get-help/" target="_blank"&gt;office hours&lt;/a&gt;, or by scheduling a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/" target="_blank"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://columbiauniversity.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJMsde2rrT4rG9VRo-waNqyd28czUUN2YrG5" target="_blank"&gt;Register here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Abstract: Hiding transmitted signals is of paramount importance in many communicationsettings. While traditional security (e.g., encryption) prevents unauthorized access tomessage content, detection of the mere presence of a message by the adversary can havea significant negative impact. This necessitates the use of covert communication, which notonly protects the information contained in a transmission from unauthorized decoding, butalso prevents the detection of a transmission in the first place. Although practical radio-frequency covert communication systems have been around since the advent of spread-spectrum, exploration of their fundamental limits is a new direction in information theory.Surprisingly, analysis of covert communication systems reveals that, while the Shannoncapacity of a covert communication channel is zero, it still allows transmission of a largevolume of covert data. This is true even when covert communications are secure fromdetection by a quantum-enabled adversary.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this talk, I will present these fundamentalresults, focusing on their intuitive explanation, rather than their mathematical derivations. Iwill also describe a table-top proof-of-concept validation that paved the way for the ongoingexperimental studies in quantum-secure covert communication.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Bio: Boulat A. Bash received the B.A. degree in economics from Dartmouth College in 2001and the M.S. and Ph.D. degrees in computer science from the University of Massachusetts,Amherst, MA, in 2008 and 2015, respectively. He is currently an Assistant Professor withthe Electrical and Computer Engineering Department at the University of Arizona, Tucson,AZ. He was previously a Scientist with the Quantum Information Processing Group atRaytheon BBN Technologies, Cambridge, MA. His research interests include security,privacy, communications, signal processing, and information theory. He won an honorablemention at the 2015 NSA Best Scientific Cybersecurity Paper Competition, the RaytheonSpace and Airborne Systems Excellence in Engineering and Technology Award, and theNSF CAREER award.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Host: Gil Zussman&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.modupeakinola.com/"&gt;Modupe Akinola&lt;/a&gt;, Associate Professor of Management and Director of the Bernstein Center for Leadership and Ethics at Columbia Business School, will lead chairs, senior faculty, and other academic leaders in a discussion about recognizing, understanding, and supporting BIPOC faculty colleagues in managing and utilizing stress in the department and across the university.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Prof. Akinola will guide us in answering questions such as:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How do we understand stress for BIPOC faculty in our academic department?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How do we address and overcome our colleagues&amp;rsquo; stress so that more people can feel welcome and thrive in environments where there is little diversity?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How might we change our own stress mindsets to better understand and support our BIPOC colleagues?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The session will further help participants in understanding where minoritized faculty are experiencing organizational life differently because of the unique stressors they face. Akinola will emphasize interventions for lasting change in the academic department.&lt;/p&gt;
