&lt;p&gt;ABOUT TISSUE TALKS&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join us every Wednesday at 3:00PM ET for the popular Tissue Talks, our weekly webinar series hosted by Dr. Gordana Vunjak-Novakovic and the Laboratory for Stem Cells and Tissue Engineering. Don&amp;rsquo;t miss the opportunity each week to hear from global leaders in Tissue Engineering!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hans-Hermann Wessels, PhD, Postdoctoral Research Scientist&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1. New York Genome Center, New York, NY, USA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;2. Center for Genomics and Systems Biology, Department of Biology, New York University, New York, NY, USA&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;New frontiers in transcriptome engineering with CRISPR-Cas13&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With the discovery of RNA-targeting CRISPR effectors (i.e., Cas13d), we now have the capability to directly target RNA with high efficiency and specificity. This Cas13d-mediated target RNA knockdown can be superior to existing DNA-targeting CRISPR technologies, enabling unambiguous targeting of non-coding RNAs, RNA isoforms, or RNA viruses; and delivery of multiple guide RNAs (gRNAs) at the same time. Here, I am highlighting the utility of Cas13d for the scientific community, first by thoroughly defining the requirements for gRNA design and by developing a pipeline for transcriptome-wide forward genetic pooled screens. And finally, by combining the high throughput of pooled Cas13 screens with content-rich phenotyping of single-cell perturbation approaches to study genetic interactions with multimodal readout.&lt;/p&gt;

