&lt;p&gt;Please join us at an in-person &lt;strong&gt;Town Hall&lt;/strong&gt; with Dr. &lt;a href="https://www.noaa.gov/our-people/leadership/richard-w-spinrad-phd"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Richard Spinrad&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans &amp;amp; Atmosphere and Administrator of the &lt;a href="https://www.noaa.gov/"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;National Oceanic &amp;amp; Atmospheric Administration&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (NOAA). The details are as follows:&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NOAA Town Hall&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Friday, March 25, 2022&lt;br /&gt;
12:30 p.m. - 1:45 p.m.&lt;br /&gt;
Monell Auditorium, Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory&lt;br /&gt;
61 Route 9W, Palisades, NY, 10964&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;NOAA is one of the most important and visionary research sponsors for the Climate School and the Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory; over the last five years, NOAA has awarded us 65 projects totaling $35M. As NOAA advances its new strategic plan - prioritizing the Blue Economy, local climate services, and equity and inclusion - this is an important opportunity for us to showcase our community&amp;rsquo;s research innovation and impact, influence the agency&amp;rsquo;s priorities, and forge increasingly meaningful long-term partnerships.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Town Hall will include lightning talks by Columbia researchers, a strategic plan presentation by Dr. Spinrad, and an opportunity for Questions &amp;amp; Answers. Remote attendance will not be possible at this time.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We very much hope that you will join us for this Town Hall in-person in the Monell Auditorium on the Lamont campus; for our colleagues based on other campuses, we encourage you to take advantage of the &lt;a href="https://transportation.columbia.edu/content/lamont-shuttle"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Intercampus Shuttle&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

